<HEADLINE> Cambodian Senators Sworn in at Royal Palace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's newly appointed 61
Senators were sworn in Thursday at the Royal Palace by King
Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
Opening ceremony started in its headquarters in Chamcar Mon
Palace. Newly appointed Senate President Chea Sim confirmed the
credentials of each of the 61 senators and gave an inaugural
speech.
</P>
<P>
"The creation of the Senate of the Kingdom is a major political
event. It provides a guarantee to political stability and liberal
democracy in Cambodia," Chea Sim said.
</P>
<P>
Present at the ceremony were Prime Minister Hun Sen and
President of National Assembly Prince Norodom Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
The senators then proceeded to the Royal Palace to be sworn in
by King Norodom Sihanouk. In the afternoon, the senators are to
set up a committee to write the internal rules of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
King Sihanouk signed name list of senators on March 18,
presented by three major parties who have seats in the National
Assembly, that completed the process of creating Senate.
</P>
<P>
The Senate comprises 61 members, of whom 31 are from the
Cambodian People's Party (CPP), 21 from FUNCINPEC party, seven
from the Sam Rainsy Party, and two appointed by the king.
</P>
<P>
Chea Sim, president of CPP, was appointed as president of the
Senate, while the first and second vice presidents came from the
FUNCINPEC party.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the Senate is part of a political deal between
the CPP and FUNCINPEC that led to the establishment of the
coalition government last November.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly had approved the Constitutional
amendments after three days of debate on March 4, paving the way
for the creation of the Senate. 
</P>
